":"1410–1476","1436–1485":"1436–1485","1438–Female":"1438–Deceased","1440–1498":"1440–1498","1442–Male":"1442–Deceased","1445–1485":"1445–1485","1389–1419":"1389–1419","1393–1421":"1393–1421","1440":"1440","1393":"1393","1415":"1415","1436":"1436","1445":"1445","1500":"1500","1455":"1455","1389":"1389","1421":"1421","1476":"1476","1498":"1498","1410":"1410","1442":"1442","1420":"1420","about 1414":"about 1414","1485":"1485","about 1445":"about 1445","about 1442":"about 1442","1419":"1419","1438":"1438","Ipswich, Suffolk, England":"Ipswich, Suffolk, England","Shotley, Suffolk, England":"Shotley, Suffolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Mosell","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Jorge, Armando, Gerardo, Angel, Carolina, Elba, Francisco, Justo, Manuel, Miguel, Modesto.","English: variant of   Morrell  .","Catalan: habitational name from any of several places called Morell in Tarragona and Girona provinces or Majorica and Minorca Islands, from a vernacular form of Latin <i>Maurellus</i> ‘dark-skinned’, a diminutive of <i>Maurus</i> ‘Moor’."],"variants":[{"name":"Morrell","meanings":["English (northern): from the medieval personal name <i>Morel</i>, a diminutive of Middle English or Old French <i>More</i>. Compare   Moore  .","Americanized form of French   Morel  . Compare   Morell   3."]}]},{"name":"Margareth","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from Greek.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margaret","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]},{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretha","meanings":["from Greek.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margarethe","meanings":["from Greek.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":40,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Margareth Mosell was born in 1415, in Shotley, Suffolk, England, her father, Thomas Mosell, was 26 and her mother, Margareth Visedolou, was 22. She married Edmund Stratton in 1436, in Shotley, Suffolk, England. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 2 daughters. She died in 1476, in her hometown, at the age of 61, and was buried in Shotley, Suffolk, England."},"et":{"1415–1476":"1415–1476","1420–1500":"1420–1500","1410–1476":"1410–1476","1436–1485":"1436–1485","1438–Female":"1438–Surnud","1440–14